      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7b3692975b84f899",
      "text": "(lat. instructed ignorance), denotes with Nikolaus von Kues the insight gained by reason itself that its cognitive capacity is not able to grasp God. Human reason can advance the knowledge of finite things by arriving at ever sharper conceptual distinctions. In the divine infinite, however, the opposites coincide (coincidentia oppositorum) and the principles of reason's cognition lose their validity. When reason, instructed about its own ignorance, abandons all claims to knowledge, man can open himself to a gracious knowledge of God. [https://www.spektrum.de/lexikon/philosophie/docta-ignorantia/480 page]"
